"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>C. M.</I> 84</A>), but on the death of his only daughter about eighteen months before this essay was written Cicero's grief was unrestrained.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note8" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">8</A>
Scipio was elected consul the first time in 147 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, at the age of <SPAN CLASS="whole">thirty-eight</SPAN>, when a candidate for the <SPAN CLASS="whole">aedile</SPAN>&shy;ship, and given command of the war against Carthage. He was elected again in 134 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> (though not a candidate), to conduct the siege against Numantia and to end a war which had gone on unsuccessfully for the Romans for eight years.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note9" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref9
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9</A>
Scipio's mother, Papiria, had been divorced by Paulus, and Scipio gave her the legacy received by him from his adoptive grandmother, Aemilia, wife of Scipio the Elder. After his mother's death he gave the same property to his sisters.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note10" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">10</A>
