<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note11" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref11
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">11</A>
<I>i.e.</I> the Pythagoreans who had a school of philosophy at Crotona in the fifth century <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note12" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref12
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">12</A>
<I>i.e.</I> lower Italy.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note13" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">13</A>
The three pairs are Theseus and Pirithous, Achilles and Patroclus, Orestes and Pylades; the fourth, probably in Cicero's mind (Cic.
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/de_Officiis/3B*.html#Damon_and_Phintias
	"TARGET="Cicero_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Off.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.45</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/de_Finibus/2*.html#Phintias
	"TARGET="Cicero_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Fin.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.79</A>), was Damon and Phintias (<I>vulg.</I> Pythias).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note14" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref14
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14</A>
<I>i.e.</I> readiness acquired by practice in extemporaneous discussion — an art practised by sophists and rhetoricians and by the philosophers of the New Academy; <I>cf.</I> Cic.
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/de_Finibus/2*.html#1
	"TARGET="Cicero_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>De Fin.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.1</A>;
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/oratore1.shtml#102
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>De or.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.102</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note15" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref15
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">15</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Id ad vivum reseco</SPAN>, lit. "cut back to the quick."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note16" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref16
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">16</A>
<I>i.e.</I> those who profess the art of disputation; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note17" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref17
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">17</A>
The perfect "wise man" of the Stoics represents an ideal, though they allowed that a few men, such as Socrates, almost realized it.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note18" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref18
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">18</A>
Lit. "at which everyone looks askance," as indicating conceit or arrogance.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify" ID="note19">
	<A CLASS="note" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/15*.html#ref19a
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19a</A>
	<A CLASS="note" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/15*.html#ref19b
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">19b</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Propinquitas</SPAN> may be applied to "neighbours" or "fellow-citizens" as well as to "relatives."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note20" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref20
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">20</A>
The ideally perfect men of the Stoics.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note21" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref21
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">21</A>
Or more literally "adaptabilities," "occasions when it can be fitly used."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note22" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref22
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">22</A>
Proverbial, that is, as representing the prime necessities of life.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note23" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref23
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">23</A>
<I>Cf.</I> Bacon's <I>Friendship</I>: "This communicating of a man's self to his friend worketh two contrary effects; for it redoubleth joys and cutteth Griefs in Halves."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note24" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Laelius_de_Amicitia/text*.html#ref24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">24</A>
Empedocles, according to whom <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">φιλότης</SPAN> (friendship) and <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">νεῖκος</SPAN> (strife) are perpetually at war, causing the four elements to unite or disperse,

<DIV ALIGN="center"><TABLE CLASS="Greek verse">
	<TR>
		<TD>
			<P>
ἄλλοτε μὲν φιλότητι συνερχόμεν’ εἰς ἓν ἅπαντα,
			<P>
ἄλλοτε δ’ αὖ δίχ’ ἕκαστα φορεύμενα νείκεος ἔχθει.
		</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note25" HREF="
